{"continue":{"rvcontinue":"20180910191450|858955936","continue":"||"},"warnings":{"main":{"*":"Subscribe to the mediawiki-api-announce mailing list at <https://lists.wikimedia.org/mailman/listinfo/mediawiki-api-announce> for notice of API deprecations and breaking changes. Use [[Special:ApiFeatureUsage]] to see usage of deprecated features by your application."},"revisions":{"*":"Because \"rvslots\" was not specified, a legacy format has been used for the output. This format is deprecated, and in the future the new format will always be used."}},"query":{"normalized":[{"from":"Scott_Perry_(politician)","to":"Scott Perry (politician)"}],"pages":{"19558869":{"pageid":19558869,"ns":0,"title":"Scott Perry (politician)","revisions":[{"timestamp":"2018-09-17T20:51:34Z","contentformat":"text/x-wiki","contentmodel":"wikitext","*":"{{other people|Scott Perry}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Scott Perry\n|image        = Scott Perry official photo.jpg\n|state        = [[Pennsylvania]]\n|district     = {{ushr|PA|4|4th}}\n|term_start   = January 3, 2013\n|term_end     =\n|predecessor  = [[Jason Altmire]]\n|successor    =\n|state_house1 = Pennsylvania\n|district1    = [[Pennsylvania House of Representatives, District 92|92nd]]\n|term_start1  = January 2, 2007\n|term_end1    = November 30, 2012\n|predecessor1 = [[Bruce Smith (Pennsylvania politician)|Bruce Smith]]\n|successor1   = [[Mike Regan (politician)|Mike Regan]]\n|birth_name   = Scott Gordon Perry\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1962|5|27}}\n|birth_place  = [[San Diego]], [[California]], U.S.\n|death_date   =\n|death_place  =\n|party        = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse       = Christy Perry\n|children     = 2\n|education    = [[Pennsylvania State University]] ([[Bachelor of Science|BS]])<br>[[United States Army War College]] ([[Master of Science|MS]])\n|website      = {{url|perry.house.gov|House website}}\n|allegiance   = {{flag|United States}}\n|branch       = {{army|United States}}\n|serviceyears = 1980\u2013present\n|rank         = [[File:US-O7 insignia.svg|18px]] [[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]]\n|commands     = {{ublist|2nd Battalion (General Support), 104th Aviation Regiment|166th Regiment (Regional Training Institute)|[[Fort Indiantown Gap]]}}\n|unit         = [[Pennsylvania Army National Guard]]\n|battles      = [[Iraq War]]\n}}\n'''Scott Gordon Perry''' (born May 27, 1962)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/campaign-2012/candidates/scott-gordon-perry-61618 |title=Scott Gordon Perry |publisher=Washington Times |agency=Associated Press |access-date=December 15, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140722195648/http://www.washingtontimes.com/campaign-2012/candidates/scott-gordon-perry-61618/ |archive-date=July 22, 2014 |dead-url=yes }}</ref> is the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S Representative]] for {{ushr|PA|4}}, serving since 2013. A member of the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]], he previously served as a member of the [[Pennsylvania House of Representatives]] for the [[Pennsylvania House of Representatives, District 92|92nd legislative district]] (2007\u20132013). Perry is also a [[Brigadier general (United States)|Brigadier General]] in the [[Pennsylvania Army National Guard]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nPerry was born in San Diego, and his family moved to Pennsylvania when he was seven years old.<ref>{{cite news |last=Neff |first=Blake |date=February 3, 2014 |title=Perry's hard road to Capitol Hill |url=http://thehill.com/capital-living/new-member-of-the-week/197212-perrys-hard-road-to-capitol-hill |work=The Hill |location=Washington, DC |ref={{sfnRef|\"Perry's hard road to Capitol Hill\"}}}}</ref> His mother and stepfather often struggled to find work, and their house had no running water nor electricity.{{sfn|\"Perry's hard road to Capitol Hill\"}}  Perry and his brother began working at an early age to help supplement the family income, and from age 13 until he was in his 20s his jobs included fruit picker, draftsman, dockworker, and insurance agent.{{sfn|\"Perry's hard road to Capitol Hill\"}}  In 1980, he graduated from [[Northern High School (Dillsburg, Pennsylvania)|Northern High School]] and the [[Northern York County School District|Cumberland-Perry Vo-Tech School]].<ref name=bio>{{cite web|title=Rep. Scott Perry bio|publisher=Pennsylvania House Republican Caucus |year=2008|url=http://www.repperry.com/?sectionid=2&sectiontree=2|access-date=January 11, 2009}}</ref> In 1991, he graduated from [[Pennsylvania State University]], where he earned a Bachelor of Science degree in Business Administration Management. In July 2012, he earned a master's degree in strategic planning from the [[United States Army War College]].<ref name=votesmart>{{cite web |title=Representative Scott Perry profile|work=Project Vote Smart|publisher=Project Vote Smart|year=2008|url=http://www.votesmart.org/bio.php?can_id=59980|access-date=January 9, 2009}}</ref>\n\n==Military service==\n===Army National Guard===\nPerry began his military career in 1980 when he enlisted in the [[Pennsylvania Army National Guard]].<ref name=dvids>{{cite web |url=https://www.dvidshub.net/news/181997/pa-army-national-guard-names-new-general |title=Pa. Army National Guard names new general |publisher=[[DVIDS|Defense Video Imagery Distribution System]] |date=November 15, 2015 |access-date=June 22, 2017 |first=Neil |last=Gussman }}</ref> He attended basic training at [[Fort Dix, New Jersey]],<ref name=dvids /> and graduated from [[Advanced Individual Training]]<ref>{{cite web |url=https://votesmart.org/candidate/biography/59980/scott-perry |title=Scott Perry's Biography |access-date=June 22, 2017 |publisher=Vote Smart }}</ref> at [[Fort Belvoir, Virginia]] as a technical drafting specialist.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://gotyour6.org/served-our-country-in-the-military-and-now-in-office-congressman-elect-scott-perry/ |title=Served Our Country in the Military and Now in Office \u2013 Congressman-Elect Scott Perry |access-date=June 22, 2017 |date=December 13, 2012 |website=gotyour6.org }}</ref> He graduated from Pennsylvania's [[Officer Candidate School]] and was commissioned a [[second lieutenant]] in the Field Artillery.<ref name=dvids />\n\nAfter receiving his commission, Perry qualified as a helicopter pilot in the Aviation branch.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nationalguard.mil/Leadership/NGB-GOMO/bio-show/2933/ |title=Biography, Brigadier General Scott Perry |date=2015 |website=National Guard General Officer Management Office |publisher=National Guard Bureau |location=Arlington, VA |access-date=June 2, 2018 |ref={{sfnRef|\"Biography, Brigadier General Scott Perry\"}}}}</ref>  He served in a variety of staff and command assignments as he advanced through the ranks, including executive officer of 1st Battalion, 104th Cavalry Regiment during deployment to [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] in 2002\u20132003, and commander of 2nd Battalion (General Support), 104th Aviation Regiment beginning in 2008.{{sfn|\"Biography, Brigadier General Scott Perry\"}}\n\n===War in Iraq===\nIn 2009\u20132010, Perry commanded 2nd Battalion, 104th Aviation Regiment during its pre-deployment training and service in Iraq for [[Operation Iraqi Freedom]].{{sfn|\"Biography, Brigadier General Scott Perry\"}} As Task Force Diablo, 2-104th Aviation was credited with flying 1,400 missions, accruing over 13,000 combat flight hours, and transporting over 3 million pounds of cargo and 43,000 soldiers and civilians.{{sfn|\"Biography, Brigadier General Scott Perry\"}}  Perry was credited with flying 44 missions and accruing nearly 200 combat flight hours.{{sfn|\"Biography, Brigadier General Scott Perry\"}}\n\n===Post-Iraq===\nAfter returning from Iraq, Perry was promoted to colonel and assigned to command the Pennsylvania National Guard's 166th Regiment (Regional Training Institute) (2010\u20132012).{{sfn|\"Biography, Brigadier General Scott Perry\"}}  From 2012 to 2014, Perry commanded the garrison at the [[Fort Indiantown Gap]] National Training Center.{{sfn|\"Biography, Brigadier General Scott Perry\"}}  In May 2014, Perry was assigned as one of the assistant division commanders of the [[28th Infantry Division (United States)|28th Infantry Division]], and he was promoted to [[Brigadier general (United States)|brigadier general]] in November 2015.<ref name=dvids />  In May 2016, Perry was assigned as assistant adjutant general for Army at the Pennsylvania National Guard's Joint Force Headquarters.{{sfn|\"Biography, Brigadier General Scott Perry\"}}\n\n===Awards and decorations===\nPerry's awards and decorations include:{{sfn|\"Biography, Brigadier General Scott Perry\"}}\n{{columns-list|colwidth=25em|\n* [[Bronze Star Medal]]\n* [[Meritorious Service Medal (United States)|Meritorious Service Medal]] w/ Bronze Oak Leaf Cluster\n* [[Joint Service Commendation Medal]]\n* [[Army Commendation Medal]] w/ Bronze Oak Leaf Cluster\n* [[Army Achievement Medal]] w/2 Bronze OLC\n* [[Army Reserve Components Achievement Medal]] w/Silver OLC and three Bronze Oak Leaf Clusters\n* [[National Defense Service Medal]] w/Bronze service star\n* [[Armed Forces Expeditionary Medal]]\n* [[Armed Forces Reserve Medal]] w/Gold hour glass, \"M\" device, and \"2\" device\n* [[Army Service Ribbon]]\n* [[Army Reserve Components Overseas Training Ribbon]] w/\"4\" device\n* [[Iraq Campaign Medal]]\n* [[Global War on Terrorism Service Medal]]\n* [[Overseas Service Ribbon]]\n* [[NATO Medal]]\n* Pennsylvania 20 Year Service Medal w/two Silver Stars\n* MG T.R. White Medal\n* Gen. T.J. Stewart Medal\n* [[Master Army Aviator Badge]]\n}}\n\n===Dates of promotion===\nSince receiving his commission in 1984, Perry's effective dates of promotion are:{{sfn|\"Biography, Brigadier General Scott Perry\"}}\n* Brigadier general, 28 September 2015\n* Colonel, 22 December 2010\n* Lieutenant colonel, 14 April 2005\n* Major, 13 July 1998\n* Captain, 6 September 1990\n* First lieutenant, 18 May 1987\n* Second lieutenant, 19 May 1984\n\n==Hydrotech==\nIn 1993, Perry founded Hydrotech Mechanical Services, Inc., a mechanical contracting firm in [[Dillsburg, Pennsylvania|Dillsburg]]. The firm provides contract construction and maintenance services to municipal and investor-owned utilities from [[North Carolina]] to [[New York (state)|New York]] specializing in large meter calibration. In 2002, the [[Pennsylvania Department of Environmental Protection]] accused the company of altering sewage monitoring reports while doing work for the Memphord Estates Sewage Treatment Company. Perry faced charges of conspiring to falsify state-mandated sewage records. Upon review of the situation and circumstances, he was allowed to complete a diversion program and avoid any charges, which allowed him to keep his U.S security clearance.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Trimmer|first1=Eric|title=Candidate emerges as Smith's successor|url=http://www.eveningsun.com/localnews/ci_3365139|access-date=8 October 2014|publisher=The Hanover Evening Sun|date=January 2, 2006}}</ref> Perry maintains his innocence.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Scolforo|first1=Mark|title=Arrest records of state lawmakers raise questions of standards|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/news/politics-state/2010/11/14/Arrest-records-of-state-lawmakers-raise-questions-of-standards/stories/201011140255|access-date=October 8, 2014|publisher=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=November 14, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Pennsylvania House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\nIn 2006, State Representative [[Bruce Smith (Pennsylvania politician)|Bruce Smith]] of Pennsylvania's 92nd House District decided to retire. Perry won the Republican primary with 41% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=277819 |title=PA State House 092 \u2013 R Primary Race \u2013 May 16, 2006 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |access-date=December 15, 2015}}</ref> He won the general election with 71% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=291742 |title=PA State House 092 Race \u2013 Nov 07, 2006 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |access-date=December 15, 2015}}</ref> He took office on January 2, 2007.<ref>{{cite web|title=SESSION OF 2007 191ST OF THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY No. 1|work=LEGISLATIVE JOURNAL |publisher =Pennsylvania House of Representatives|date=January 2, 2007 |url=http://www.legis.state.pa.us/WU01/LI/HJ/2007/0/20070102.PDF|access-date=January 9, 2009}}</ref> In 2008, he won re-election to a second term unopposed.<ref name=\"ourcampaigns.com\">{{cite web |url=http://www.ourcampaigns.com/RaceDetail.html?RaceID=440799 |title=PA State House 092 Race \u2013 Nov 04, 2008 |publisher=Our Campaigns |date= |access-date=December 15, 2015}}</ref> In 2010, he won re-election to a third term unopposed.<ref name=\"ourcampaigns.com\"/>\n\n===Committee assignments===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=25em|\n* Appropriations\n* Rules\n* Labor Relations\n* Consumer Affairs\n* Veterans Affairs and Emergency Preparedness<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repperry.com/bio.aspx |title=Biography |publisher=Repperry.com |access-date=December 15, 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121126020717/http://www.repperry.com/bio.aspx |dead-url=yes |archive-date=November 26, 2012 }}</ref>\n}}\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\nPerry is a member of the [[Freedom Caucus]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.rollcall.com/218/house-freedom-caucus-forms-fight-club/|title=House Freedom Caucus Forms 'Fight Club' in House|work=218|date=July 22, 2015|access-date=February 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, Perry suggested that ISIS may have committed the [[2017 Las Vegas shooting]], in contrast to local and federal law enforcement officials' assertions that it was committed by Stephen Paddock who had no ISIS affiliation.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/house/369672-gop-lawmaker-somethings-not-adding-up-on-las-vegas-shooting|title=GOP lawmaker: 'Something's not adding up' on Las Vegas shooting|last=Samuels|first=Brett|date=2018-01-18|work=TheHill|access-date=2018-01-19}}</ref>\n\n===Elections===\n;2012\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2012#District 4}}\nIn 2012, Perry gave up his state house seat to run for the 4th congressional district. The district had previously been the 19th District, represented by six-term incumbent Republican [[Todd Platts]], who was giving up the seat to honor a self-imposed term limit. In 2010, when Platts wanted to become the [[Comptroller General of the United States|U.S. Comptroller General]], he spoke to Perry about his running for the seat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ydr.com/politics/ci_19779324 |title=USA TODAY: Latest World and US News \u2013 USATODAY.com |publisher=Ydr.com |date= |access-date=December 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\nPerry won a seven-way primary with over 50% of the vote.  Although being outspent nearly 2 to 1 throughout the campaign he was able to beat his closest competitor on election day with nearly 3 times as many votes.\n\nOn November 6, 2012, Perry defeated [[Democratic Party (US)|Democrat]] Harry Perkinson 60%\u201334%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elections.nytimes.com/2012/results/house |title=House Map \u2013 Election 2012 \u2013 NYTimes.com |publisher=Elections.nytimes.com |date= |access-date=December 15, 2015}}</ref>\n\n;2014\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2014#District 4}}\nIn 2014, Perry was unchallenged in the Republican primary. His Democratic party challenger in the general election was former mayor of [[Harrisburg, Pennsylvania|Harrisburg]], [[Linda D. Thompson]].  Perry won the general election 75%\u201325%.<ref name=PAgeneral>{{cite web |url=http://www.electionreturns.state.pa.us/Default.aspx?EID=41&ESTID=2&CID=0&OID=11&CDID=0&PID=0&DISTID=0&IsSpecial=0&PageRefID=1 |title=Pennsylvania 2014 General Election \u2013 November 4, 2014 Official Results |publisher=Pennsylvania Secretary of State |date=November 4, 2014 |access-date=January 16, 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150215091446/http://www.electionreturns.state.pa.us/Default.aspx?EID=41&ESTID=2&CID=0&OID=11&CDID=0&PID=0&DISTID=0&IsSpecial=0&PageRefID=1 |archivedate=February 15, 2015 |df= }}</ref>\n\n;2016\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2016#District 4}}\nPerry was unchallenged in the 2016 Republican primary. His Democratic Party challenger in the general election was Joshua Burkholder of Harrisburg.<ref name=statusquo>{{cite web |url=http://www.pennlive.com/news/2016/02/pas_congressional_races_like_s.html|title=Pa's Congressional race lineup: Like status quo? Voters will get chance to keep it.|work=[[The Patriot-News]] |last=Thompson|first=Charles|date=February 17, 2016|access-date=February 18, 2016}}</ref> Perry won the election 66%\u201334%.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.cnn.com/election/results/states/pennsylvania/house/04|title=Full 2016 election results: Pennsylvania House 04|website=www.cnn.com|access-date=November 12, 2016}}</ref>\n\n;2018\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Pennsylvania, 2018#District 10}}\n\n=== Ratings ===\nPerry has received the following ratings from advocacy organizations:<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.govtrack.us/congress/members/scott_perry/412569|title=Scott Perry, Representative for Pennsylvania's 4th Congressional District - GovTrack.us|website=GovTrack.us|language=en|access-date=2018-09-17}}</ref>\n\n* FreedomWorks: 100%\n* Americans for Prosperity: 94%\n* The Club for Growth: 91%\n* United States Chamber of Commerce: 98%\n* The National Organization for the Reform of Marijuana Laws: B+\n* League of Conservation Voters: 3%\n* Planned Parenthood Action Fund: 0%\n\n===Committee assignments===\n{{columns-list|colwidth=25em|\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Foreign Affairs|Committee on Foreign Affairs]]'''\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Asia and the Pacific|Subcommittee on Asia and the Pacific]]\n** [[United States House Foreign Affairs Subcommittee on Terrorism, Nonproliferation, and Trade|Subcommittee on Terrorism, Nonproliferation, and Trade]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Homeland Security|Committee on Homeland Security]]'''\n** [[United States House Homeland Security Subcommittee on Cybersecurity, Infrastructure Protection, and Security Technologies|Subcommittee on Cybersecurity, Infrastructure Protection, and Security Technologies]]\n** [[United States House Homeland Security Subcommittee on Emergency Preparedness, Response, and Communications|Subcommittee on Emergency Preparedness, Response, and Communications]]\n* '''[[United States House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure|Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure]]'''\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Economic Development, Public Buildings and Emergency Management|Subcommittee on Economic Development, Public Buildings and Emergency Management]]\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Highways and Transit|Subcommittee on Highways and Transit]]\n** [[United States House Transportation Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials|Subcommittee on Railroads, Pipelines, and Hazardous Materials]]\n}}\n\n===''Who is America?'' segment===\nIn 2018, Perry was pranked by comedian [[Sacha Baron Cohen]] into accepting the non-existent \"70 for 70\" award, supposedly in recognition of the anniversary of the founding [[Israel]], in a segment on Cohen's [[mockumentary]] show ''[[Who is America?]]''.<ref>{{cite news |last=Hermann |first=Adam |date=August 3, 2018 |title=Rep. Scott Perry still touts his fake Sacha Baron Cohen award  |url=https://www.phillyvoice.com/scott-perry-fake-sacha-baron-cohen-award/ |work=Philly Voice |location=Philadelphia, PA}}</ref> After Cohen's revelation that it is not a real award, Perry's campaign website continued until August 7, 2018 to include \"70 for 70\" among the honors and recognition he has received. Perry issued a statement on August 3 acknowledging the error and questioning its newsworthiness.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.yorkdispatch.com/story/news/local/2018/08/08/scott-perry-falls-victim-sacha-baron-cohen-prank-who-america/936272002/ |newspaper=York Dispatch |first=Logan |last=Hullinger |date=August 8, 2018\n|access-date=August 13, 2018 |title=Scott Perry falls victim to Sacha Baron Cohen prank on 'Who is America?' }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://perry.house.gov/ Congressman Scott Perry] official U.S. House website\n* [http://www.patriotsforperry.com/ Scott Perry for Congress]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Pennsylvania/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Scott_Perry_%5BR-4%5D|Scott Perry}}\n* {{C-SPAN|scottperry}}\n* {{CongLinks | congbio=P000605 | votesmart=59980 | fec=H2PA04135 | congress=scott-perry/2157 }}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-pa-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Bruce Smith (Pennsylvania politician)|Bruce Smith]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[Pennsylvania House of Representatives]]<br>from the [[Pennsylvania House of Representatives, District 92|92nd]] district|years=2007\u20132012}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Mike Regan (politician)|Mike Regan]]}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{USRepSuccessionBox\n| state=Pennsylvania\n| district=4\n| before=[[Jason Altmire]]\n| start=2013\n}}\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Beto O'Rourke]]<br>D-[[Texas]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=''[[List of current members of the United States House of Representatives by seniority|United States Representatives by seniority]]''|years=284th}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Scott Peters (politician)|Scott Peters]]<br>D-[[California]]}}\n{{end}}\n\n{{PA-FedRep}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n{{Members of the U.S. House of Representatives from Pennsylvania}}\n{{USCongRep-start|congresses= 113th\u2013115th [[United States Congress]] |state=[[Pennsylvania]]}}\n{{USCon